I have no less than three issues with Sakura. First, for a karaoke bar there was no institutional interaction with the song request list such that other patrons could actively delete other song requests and advance their own without any repercussions. Second, there was no explanation of the interface to request songs. Anyone not fluent in the language on screen was essentially left to their devices. Finally, and most frustratingly, the bartenders lost track of my credit card and ID  leading to my being overcharged and instigating an argument with management over politics

(Translated by Google) A clean Chinese karaoke room in Chinatown. It is a combination of bars and karaoke, and you can sing openly in a wide hall. Even if you do not drink alcohol, you need an ID card to enter. It is a feeling of chinese-style cha-lang and it is visited by people of various nationalities regardless of country. The karaoke rental costs $ 35 an hour and includes 18% tips. For non-Chinese people it is very difficult to find songs. Unlike Korean karaoke, it does not control the height of songs and it is very difficult to search for songs in Korean and Japanese.  (Original) 차이나타운에 위치한 그나마 깨끗한 중국노래방. 바와 노래방이 같이 결합된 형태이며 넓은 홀에서도 공개적으로 노래를 할 수 있다. 술을 시키지 않더라도 입장하기 위해서는 신분증이 꼭 필요하다. 중국풍의 단란주점 느낌이며 나라를 불문하고 다양한 국적의 사람들이 방문한다. 노래방 대여료는 한 시간에 35불이며 18%팁이 무조건 포함된다. 중국인 외의 사람들에게는 노래를 찾는 것이 상당히 힘들다. 한국 노래방과는 다르게 노래의 키를 조절하는 것도 없고 한국어, 일본어로 노래를 검색하는 것이 매우 힘들다.

They have most if not all of the classics, and a few cherrypicked songs from less mainstream artists/bands. Nice environment since they redecorated. Food/drinks were pricy but that's to be expected. My biggest  (and only) compliant was how they got rid of their customers. Once our time was up, a server came in, propped the door open, turned on the lights, grabbed the nearest bus boy (who was in the middle of busing another table) and made him stand there as we collect our things. What made it awkward was we kept waiting for our credit cards to be returned to us so he just was watching us sitting there waiting while the door was open and it was loud. If they are so concerned with over staying customers, other karaoke establishments will flip your screens to a "come again" message and prevent customers from continuing to sing. It was a pretty fun night until they herded us out like they never wanted to see us again. For what it's worth, the bus boy tried to be very polite about the situation when we left.

Saturday night and had a good time with friends because we made the best of it. And bouncer was friendly. (Scroll down if you want review only on karaoke)  But  Private room and bathroom dirty.  Drinks: The mixed drinks were not good. The bartender said she can make me a basic lime margarita but then asked me what goes into it (its your job to know) so i just got their Hennessey tea instead but you can really taste the liquor. needed honey or sugar.  Service: They also tried to rush us out of our $40/hour private room (stopped in our room at the half hour, 15, 10 , and 5 minute markers before our time was over to remind us that we leave at 1). They never checked to see how things were going. And being in chinatown, their service wasnt great for our non-asian looking group.  Automatically charged 18% gratuity for them to pick up empty cups. They didn't bring us drinks or offered any assistance or to take any order if we wanted food.  Karaoke selection/system: cool with the touch screen but it froze on us and wasted 5-10 minutes of our room time, which we didnt get back and wasnt given something for (they also knew that song messes up the system: so why do you still have it?). song selection is not organized well and is missing karoke classics. Qlso no "top choices" or "todays hits" or even a genre selection. Decent artists but the songs for them were unpopular songs. Lots of duplicate songs. Lame music videos that looked like it was made in the early 90s if it wasnt the official video. ( we had a video play of a woman walking along the beach for Usher -" yeah"). both mics in the room ran out of battery quickly and had a lot of feedback.

Every one was right..the lychee martini was oh sooo good.  I had 3 all by myself!  My friends and I came here for a birthday celebration and booked the large room.  It was a good idea that we did because we got to sing all the songs we wanted without waiting and we also had a private bathroom!  The karaoke and sound system are more technologically advanced than some of the other karaoke bars I've seen.  Everything is touch screen.  The only downside was their selection of songs.  There were a lot of Chinese songs (which I understand since it is in Chinatown) but there wasn't much variety of English songs.  There wasn't much service though.  If you need a drink or something to eat, you will have to walk out to the bar to order one.  Oh, and biggest mistake is for them not to serve tap water!!!!  They force you to buy bottled water for a ridiculous price!  Seriously?  I don't think that's legal by the way.  But other than that fluke, everyone enjoyed themselves and it was overall a great time.
This is a great place to go out with friends, have a few drinks and sing your butt off.

I went to Sakura with a large group of co-workers. We found a comfortable place to sit, had a few drinks that were moderately priced. When it came to requesting songs, the setup was easy enough to navigate. The problem came when I selected a few songs and waited for two hours for them to play. I stood there and watched as the attendant (who didn't look much older than 18) continually moved his own selections in front of mine. Friends of mine went up and addressed to issue, because I didn't want to start any problems, yet he kept moving me down the list. Eventually our group left due to the fact that he was being so rude and failing to take the customer into consideration.
